{"title":"Mind Your Step (by Step): Chain-of-Thought can Reduce Performance on Tasks where Thinking Makes Humans Worse","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"Practitioners lack a principled way to predict when chain-of-thought (CoT) will reduce model performance, despite its widespread default use.","method":"Draw a heuristic from cognitive psychology: identify task archetypes where human verbal thinking impairs performance, then test whether CoT similarly harms LLM/LMMs. The authors scale six representative tasks into large evaluations (released as a benchmark) and compare zero-shot vs. CoT across many state-of-the-art models, finding large CoT-induced drops in three archetypes (implicit statistical learning, stimuli ill-suited to language such as faces, and rules-with-exceptions). A bootstrap analysis against 378 prior CoT comparisons shows the heuristic disproportionately surfaces failures (p<1e-4 by magnitude; p<1.1e-4 by frequency), and the benchmark is available at https://github.com/JiayiGeng/CoT_overthinking."},{"problem":"In implicit statistical learning (e.g., artificial grammar learning), patterns are often recognized implicitly and are hard to verbalize; CoT may force suboptimal verbal reasoning and reduce accuracy.","method":"Replicate and massively scale artificial grammar learning to 100 finite-state grammars (4400 problems), evaluating nine SOTA models with zero-shot vs. CoT. CoT consistently lowers accuracy (e.g., GPT-4o: −23.1% absolute; Claude 3 Opus: −8.0%; Gemini 1.5 Pro: −6.05%; Llama 3.1 70B: −8.8%), and o1-preview (with built-in reasoning) underperforms GPT-4o zero-shot by 36.3% on a subset. The effect persists across grammar complexities; tree-of-thought yields only small gains (64.55% vs 62.52% CoT) and remains far below zero-shot (94.00%), and results are robust to temperature and in-context steering toward bigram strategies."},{"problem":"When classifying data governed by a simple rule with exceptions, CoT may bias models toward overgeneralizing the rule, slowing learning despite explicit in-context feedback.","method":"Adapt a multi-turn vehicle classification task with feedback and long-context memory (240 lists × 10 items) where a highly correlated feature has 20% exceptions and a unique identifier feature allows perfect mapping. CoT greatly increases rounds needed to master labels (GPT-4o: +331% to 12.5 rounds; Claude 3.5 Sonnet: +178%; Claude 3 Opus: +129%), with GPT-4o’s CoT accuracy saturating near the non-exception rate (~80%) after 15 iterations. Steering prompts that explicitly focus on the exception-free identifier (e.g., license plates) can mitigate the deficit, but default CoT remains substantially worse than direct prompting."}]}
